{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:41:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:41:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1135"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1135"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.1,0.2,0.08,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108187"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1135"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90599"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2475"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"9527"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108187"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-day history of left-sided lower abdominal pain associated with vomiting and diarrhoea. Her grandson attends kindergarten locally and there was a recent outbreak of similar symptoms. She is a recent migrant from Afghanistan and has no significant medical history, although several family members have had lung issues. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well and reports that she was able to eat and drink normally. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is slightly distended and soft to palpation. Urine dipstick reveals: protein negative, blood negative, leucocytes negative, nitrites negative, glucose negative. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed, revealing an area of calcification in the right lower quadrant (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the calcification seen on the radiograph?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecolith","Gallstone","Renal calculus","Hydatid disease","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of gastroenteritis. The abdominal X-ray reveals an incidental finding of calcification in the right lower quadrant, which is likely unrelated to her current symptoms. Whilst this is a tricky presentation of asymptomatic tuberculosis, it is an important learning point of considering all parts of the history taking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for this calcification. Calcified lymph nodes due to previous tuberculosis exposure are relatively common in migrant populations from areas where tuberculosis is endemic, such as Afghanistan. This finding is consistent with the patient\u0027s background and the location of the calcification in the abdominal cavity. The family history of lung issues further supports possible tuberculosis exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially be seen at this site, but such a degree of calcification would be uncommon. Faecoliths are typically associated with appendicitis, which doesn\u0027t fit the clinical picture in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstone\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as the calcification is located too low to be within the gallbladder. Moreover, only about five per cent of gallstones contain sufficient calcium to be visible on a plain X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal calculus\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be located more laterally in the renal pelvis or upper ureter, rather than in the position shown on this X-ray. Additionally, a stone of this size would typically cause severe, colicky right-sided abdominal pain, which is not consistent with the patient\u0027s left-sided symptoms. The negative urine dipstick for blood also makes this diagnosis less likely, as renal calculi often cause microscopic haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as cystic lesions with a rim of calcification, which is not the case here. While hydatid disease can occur in patients from endemic areas, the radiographic appearance is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that there are many potential causes of calcification on abdominal X-rays, including chronic inflammation, chronic infection, degenerative processes, metabolic processes, and neoplasia. In this case, the incidental finding of calcification should be interpreted in the context of the patient\u0027s history and current presentation. The patient\u0027s acute symptoms are more likely due to gastroenteritis, and the calcification is probably an unrelated, chronic finding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Calcified mesenteric lymph nodes from previous tuberculosis infection are a common incidental finding in migrants from endemic areas.","Abdominal calcification in the right iliac fossa has a broad differential including previous tuberculosis, appendicoliths, vascular calcification, and urinary tract calculi.","The pattern and location of calcification, combined with patient demographics and clinical context, helps narrow the differential diagnosis."],"references":["Loo JT, Duddalwar V, Chen FK et al. Abdominal radiograph pearls and pitfalls for the emergency department radiologist: a pictorial review. Abdom Radiol 2017; 42:987-1019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90599"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1135"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19971"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19971"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b44c393-32d6-42c3-a920-db5b2f5ca2c9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b44c393-32d6-42c3-a920-db5b2f5ca2c9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":305,"height":353}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90599"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T09:17:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T17:35:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1135"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108187"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroe